AWS EC2 APACHE WEB SERVER DEPLOYMENT
ARCHITECTURE DESCRIPTION

PROJECT OVERVIEW
----------------
This project demonstrates the deployment of a Linux-based web server on Amazon Web Services (AWS) using an EC2 instance running Ubuntu Linux. Apache HTTP Server is installed and configured to host a custom HTML webpage that is accessible through the internet using the instance's Public IPv4 Address.

ARCHITECTURE COMPONENTS
-----------------------

1. USER / CLIENT
   - End users access the website through a web browser.
   - Requests are sent over the internet using the EC2 Public IP Address.

2. INTERNET
   - Acts as the communication medium between users and the AWS cloud infrastructure.

3. AWS CLOUD
   - Provides the cloud environment where the virtual server is deployed.

4. AMAZON EC2 INSTANCE
   - Instance Type: t3.micro
   - Operating System: Ubuntu Linux
   - Functions as the virtual server hosting the website.

5. SECURITY GROUP
   - Acts as a virtual firewall.
   - Inbound Rules:
       • SSH (Port 22)
       • HTTP (Port 80)
   - Controls incoming traffic to the EC2 instance.

6. APACHE HTTP SERVER
   - Installed on Ubuntu Linux.
   - Processes incoming HTTP requests.
   - Serves website content to users.

7. WEB APPLICATION
   - Custom HTML webpage stored in:
     /var/www/html/index.html
   - Displayed when users access the server's public IP.

8. PUBLIC IPv4 ADDRESS
   - Provides internet accessibility.
   - Maps user requests to the EC2 instance.

WORKFLOW
--------

Step 1:
User launches an Ubuntu EC2 Instance on AWS.

Step 2:
Security Group is configured to allow:
- SSH Traffic (Port 22)
- HTTP Traffic (Port 80)

Step 3:
User connects to the EC2 instance using SSH.

Step 4:
System packages are updated using:

sudo apt update
sudo apt upgrade -y

Step 5:
Apache HTTP Server is installed using:

sudo apt install apache2 -y

Step 6:
Apache service is started and verified:

sudo systemctl status apache2

Step 7:
Custom HTML webpage is created and stored in:

/var/www/html/index.html

Step 8:
Apache serves the webpage through Port 80.

Step 9:
Users access the website using the EC2 Public IPv4 Address.

